  "descriptions": [
    {
      "descrType": "Overview",
      "description": "The Eurofighter Typhoon is a European-multinational, single-seat, twin-engine, all-weather multi-role fighter aircraft developed by Eurofighter GmbH as a collaborative effort between the United Kingdom, Germany, Italy, and Spain. The aircraft entered service in 2003 and has become the primary air defense fighter for these nations, with additional exports to Austria and Saudi Arabia. The Typhoon combines canard-delta wing design, advanced digital avionics, and integrated sensor fusion to provide air superiority and ground attack capabilities.",
      "shortDescription": "European multinational fourth-generation multi-role fighter developed by UK, Germany, Italy, Spain.",
      "classification": "U"
    },
    {
      "descrType": "Design",
      "description": "The Eurofighter features a canard-delta wing planform with a highly integrated avionics suite. The airframe is constructed primarily from carbon-fiber composites and aluminum-lithium alloys to minimize weight while maximizing strength. Two EuroJet EJ200 augmented turbofan engines provide supersonic cruise capability without afterburner. The aircraft is equipped with the Captor AESA radar for air-to-air and air-to-ground operations, supplemented by the IRIS-T infrared search and track system. The Typhoon&amp;rsquo;s open architecture allows for continuous software and hardware upgrades, supporting integration of new weapons and sensors throughout its operational life.",
      "shortDescription": "Canard-delta design with EJ200 turbofan engines, Captor AESA radar, and composite airframe construction.",
      "classification": "U"
    },
    {
      "descrType": "Usage",
      "description": "The Typhoon is operated by the Royal Air Force, German Air Force, Italian Air Force, Spanish Air Force, Austrian Air Force, and Royal Saudi Air Force. The aircraft has been extensively upgraded through several tranches, with Tranche 3 aircraft introducing enhanced electronic warfare, data link, and weapons capability. The platform has seen operational deployment in training missions and air defense operations across Europe and the Middle East. Production is shared among Eurofighter partner nations, with final assembly occurring in multiple countries.",
      "shortDescription": "Operated by six nations; continuous upgrades throughout operational service; production shared among partner countries.",
      "classification": "U"
    }
  ],
